56.title: Ringworm
dlg:
Ringworms are fungi or yeast that use keratin from dead skin cells for food.

They must live on the outermost layer of the skin (dead skin cells that are filled with the protein keratin), hair, or nails to survive.

0.header:
Does this look like ringworm?

That is probably the first question you will yourself.




Let's find out if that is what you are looking at. We will be talking about ringworm of the body here.

1.header:
Listed below are a few things to know.
  • Ringworm is contagious. You can get it from direct contact with ringworm on someone's skin.

  • Touching items that have the fungi on them, such as clothing, shower floors, pool surfaces can give it to you (They thrive in warm, moist areas).

  • You can also get it from your pets especially cats.

Let's continue and see if you are looking at ringworm.

2.header: Are you looking at a patch or patches that are itchy?

3.header:
Yes?
A ringworm is sometimes itchy and like a patch that will keep expanding outwards.

4.header: Is the area scaly with dry and flaky skin surrounding it?

6.header: Does the affected area have outside red border like a ring?

7.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of ringworm infection.

The contours of the ring may be irregular with scaly borders.

Signs of a ringworm include:

  • Itchy patch or patches
  • Scaly area with dry and flaky surrounding skin
  • Outside ring like red border

8.header: Are the edges of the area defined and slightly raised?

9.header:
Yes?
This is a description of a ringworm infection.

Signs include:

  • Itchy patch or patches
  • Scaly area with dry and flaky surrounding skin
  • Outside ring like red border
  • Sharply defined borders

10.header:
Is this an area that is redder outside?

With a clear or normal skin tone in the center?

11.header:
Yes?
A ringworm may look like this.

The inside of the ring may be scaly or marked with scattered red bumps and several rings may develop at the same time and overlap.

12.header:
Alright
Those were what a ringworm infection may look like.

If you think you are looking at a ringworm infection, let's continue and see what a pharmacist recommend you use over the counter to help clear this up.

If you are still not sure, you will have to see a healthcare provider.

A healthcare provider may examine your skin in a dark room with a blue light called Wood's lamp. This will make the fungus glow if it is ringworm.

20.header:
Having to see a doctor depends on a few things listed below.

It depends on if the area is:

  • Infected due to scratching.

  • Very extensive. In which case you will need oral medications.

  • Very inflammed.

  • Mixed with other causes.

Let's make the right decision regarding this ringworm.

21.header:
Is the affected area swollen?

Warm to touch?

22.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at infection.

23.header: Is the area draining or forming pus?

24.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible infection.

25.header: Are you looking at red streaks in the affected area?

26.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible infection.

27.header: Do you have any fever in addition to this ringworm?

28.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at a serious situation if you think the ringworm is the cause.

29.header: Is the ringworm on the scalp?

30.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Hard to treat.
  • Over-the-counter creams won't cut this.
  • You will need oral prescription medication like griseofulvin.

31.header: Is the ringworm over much of the body?

32.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need oral prescription medication.
  • Cannot rub cream to a very large area. May be too expensive to do anyway.

33.header: Have you tried selfcare for 4 weeks now and still no relief?

34.header:
Time to seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need something stronger.
  • Need to make sure it is a ringworm infection.

35.header: Does this ringworm keep coming back even after going away?

36.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need further evaluation.
  • Need to keep treating for a few more weeks even after clearing.

37.header:
Those were some of the reasons to see a doctor.

If none applied to you, let's get an over-the-counter recommendation for this ringworm infection.

Or perhaps you would like to see the nearest urgent care clinic to you.

0.header:
A wart is a rough, raised, round or oval, painless growth on the skin.

They are generally harmless and often go away on their own within a few years.



You may be here because you do not like how the wart look or it is painful. .

Let's see what you can do about it.

1.header:
Is this wart on the pubic area, vaginal?

Or anal canal?

2.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at genital warts.
  • This must be treated by a doctor. Do not use over-the-counter wart removal stuff for this.
  • If you have genital warts, all of your sexual partners must be examined by a health care provider and treated if warts are found.
  • Even if you do NOT have symptoms, you must be treated to prevent complications and spreading the condition to others.

3.header: Is the wart on the face or forehead?

4.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • No over-the-counter treatment available for this.

5.header: Is the wart on the soles of the feet?

6.header:
Yes?
You are more than likely looking at plantar warts.

Plantar warts are found on the soles of the feet.

Because of their location, they can become extremely painful.

Large numbers of plantar warts on the foot may cause difficulty when running and even walking.

Let's see how you can take care of this wart.

7.header:
Is this wart mainly on the hands...
(can be anywhere else)

... and is raised, roughened or somewhat painless?

8.header:
Yes?
More than likely looking at common warts.

Let's continue and see what a pharmacist recommend you use to get rid of this wart.

9.header: Is this under and around the finger or toe nails?

10.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at subungual and periungual warts
  • Hard to treat. See a doctor for this.

11.header:
Alright.
If the wart does not fall into the categories discussed so far, see a doctor.

If it is likely a common wart, then let's continue.

20.header: Let's figure out how bad it is by answering a few questions.

21.header: Is the wart and surroundings showing red streaks or pus?

22.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at an infection.

23.header: Is the wart and surrounding area bleeding and light pressure won't stop it?

24.header: Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

25.header: Are you seeing any other type of discharge?

26.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out infection.

27.header: Is the wart very painful?

28.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need professional evaluation.

29.header: Is there any change in the color or appearance of the wart lately?

30.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out melanoma.

31.header: Are you diabetic?

32.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Hard to treat with self care.

33.header: Do you have a weakened immune system?

34.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Hard to treat with self care.

35.header: Finally, have you tried self-care and the wart has not responded and you want it removed?

36.header: Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

37.header:
Let's see what to use over-the-counter for this wart.

Like to see what a pharmacist recommend over the counter or see the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

40.header:
Is this a wart or a corn?
Let's answer that first.

41.header:
See if you can get a surgical blade or a clean fine razor blade.

Gently shave the area with the blade.

 

did it shave easily without pain or was it very painful?

43.header:
Corns will shave easily without pain.

But warts will be very painful.

Alright, one more question.

45.header: Are you seeing black dots in the center of this lesion?

46.header:
Yes?
Suspecting a wart.

Tiny blood vessels grow into a wart and may appear as dark specks that look like dirt in the center.

47.header: Is this in groups or clusters?

48.header:
Yes?
Suspecting a wart.

Warts can appear alone or in groups.

49.header:
OK
Those are some of the ways to distinguish a plantar wart from a corn.

Let's continue and see how to take care of this if you are thinking plantar warts.

58.title: Scabies
dlg:
Scabies is caused by the human itch mite when the female burrow into the upper layer of the skin to live and lay eggs.

It is usually spread by direct, prolonged, skin to skin contact with a person who has scabies.

When infested with scabies mites the first time, you usually won't know for up to 2 to 6 weeks.

But you can spread it during this time even though you do not have symptoms.

If you've had it before, the symptoms show up more quickly (about 1 to 4 days).

0.header:
Scabies is caused by the human itch mite.

Let's see if you have scabies.

A quick note:
There is no over-the-counter medication to get rid of scabies. These medications are only available with a doctor's prescription.


This exercise is geared towards helping you make a more reasonable decision as to whether you may have scabies or not so you can quickly get treatment and stop spreading it.

1.header: Do you have any fever?

3.header: What about itching with rash that look like pimples?

5.header:
Are you experiencing itching between the fingers?

Between the toes?

6.header:
Yes?
Chances of scabies are increasing. This is a sign.

7.header:
What about itching in the wrist?
(mainly inner part)

Itching in the elbows?

8.header:
Yes?
Suspect scabies if these symptoms apply.

Signs include:

  • Severe itching especially at night.
  • Itching between the fingers and toes.
  • Itching in the elbows and wrists.

9.header:
Are you experiencing itching in the buttocks or penis?

Itching in the armpit?

10.header:
Yes?
Suspect scabies if the signs below apply to you.

Signs include:

  • Severe itching especially at night.
  • Itching between the fingers and toes.
  • Itching in the elbows and wrists.
  • Itching in the armpit, buttocks, penis

You will look for burrows caused by the female scabies mite tunneling just beneath the skin surface very soon.

11.header: Is everyone in the house itching?

12.header:
Yes?
Possible scabies infestation.

Signs include:

  • Severe itching especially at night.
  • Itching between the fingers and toes.
  • Itching in the elbows and wrists.
  • Itching in the armpit, buttocks, penis
  • Other people are itching in the house.

The diagnosis is usually made based on the presence of burrows.

Also based on the appearance and distribution of the rash.

Let's look for burrows caused by the female scabies mite tunneling just beneath the skin surface.

13.header:
Alright
Those were signs of scabies infestation.

If these do not apply to you, you may not be looking at scabies.

If they do apply to you, don't panic yet.

The diagnosis of scabies is usually made based on the presence of burrows. Also based on the appearance and distribution of the rash.

Let's look for burrows caused by the female scabies mite tunneling just beneath the skin surface.

20.header:
Looking for S-shaped, tiny, raised, grayish-white lines on the skin surface.

Or skin-colored lines on the skin surface.

Let's get started and see if you can come up with anything like that.

21.header:
Look in-between the fingers and skin folds on the wrist.

Did you find these lines?

22.header:
Yes?
Try to ID the mite or mite eggs if any.

If you find any mite, carefully remove the mite from the end of its burrow using the tip of a needle if you can.

If not, don't worry, go to the nearest urgent care clinic or call your doctor to book an appointment.

Remember that only prescription lotions or creams are effective to treat scabies.

You may be tempted to try other things first like using tea tree oil and so on, but if you want to get some sleep at night, better go and see a doctor.

Would you like to find the nearest urgent care clinic to you or Continue?

23.header:
Look in-between the skin folds on the elbows.

Anything that look like S-shaped lines?

24.header:
Yes?

Carefully remove the mite from the end of its burrow using the tip of a needle if you can.

25.header:
Let's take a look at the skin folds on the knees.

Do you find any lines?

26.header:
Yes?

Carefully remove the mite from the end of its burrow using the tip of a needle if you can.

27.header:
What about on the breast and shoulder blades?

Anything?

28.header:
Yes?

Carefully remove the mite from the end of its burrow using the tip of a needle if you can.

If not, don't worry, go to the nearest urgent care clinic or call your doctor to book an appointment.

29.header:
Diagnosis is usually made based on the presence of burrows...

...and the appearance and distribution of the rash.

Seek urgent care if:

  • Most people in your household are itching at the same time

  • Itching is severe and inbetween the webbings of the fingers and or toes

  • Itching is severe and in the folds of the elbows or armpits

  • Itching more especially at night.

But for now, take some antihistamine like diphenhydramine or cetirizine to help with the itching.

Would you like to visit the nearest urgent care clinic?

There is nothing over-the-counter that will work if you are thinking scabies so no need to send you to a pharmacist for an over-the-counter recommendation.

59.title: Shingles
dlg: The same virus that cause chickenpox remains inactive in certain nerves in the body after the chickenpox. This virus can suddenly become active again if for instance your immune system is weakened or you are taking some types of medications or you come down with some disease.

If it is shingles and the blisters are:

Around the eyes:
This can lead to painful eye infections, immediate or delayed vision impairment or blindness. If you have Shingles in these areas, you should see an ophthalmologist immediately.

Around the ears:
This can lead to hearing loss or a disease called Ramsay Hunt Syndrome, in which facial nerves become paralyzed. Ramsay Hunt syndrome can cause hearing and balance problems. Muscles on the affected side of the face becomes weakened. In this case the virus has infected the facial nerve near the inner ear. If you have painful blisters in or around your ear, I will consider this a medical emergency.

Chances of recovery are better if the treatment is started within 3 days of when the symptoms begin. 70% of patients will make a full recovery if started at this time. However, if after 3 days, this drops to about 50%.

So the more severe the damage, the longer it will take to recover and the lower the chance that you will get normal again.

0.header:
If you've ever had chickenpox, then you can get shingles.

Let's try to see if you have shingles.


It is not easy to know if you have shingles before the actual outbreak of the rash.

1.header: Are you experiencing or did you experience a tingling sensation on one side of the body?

3.header: What about an itchy feeling on one side of the body?

5.header: Any burning feeling on one side of the body?

7.header: OK. Are you feeling pain that can be severe at times on one side of the body?

9.header:
A,
Those were starting signs of shingles.

The first sign of Shingles is usually a painful, burning or an itchy feeling on a single side of the body.

This sensation may last from two to three days.

It is usually present before any rash appears.

If this is all you are experiencing right now, look out for red patches on the skin followed by small blisters forming at any time (especially in the same area of the pain), tingling or burning sensation.

If you already have the rash, let's continue.

10.header: Are you looking at red patches or rash on the skin?

11.header:
No?
If you are thinking shingles, you will have to see a healthcare professional.

The discussions from here on would assume you have a skin rash or something similar.

12.header: Would you say the rash started after a burning or painful sensation?

13.header:
No?
You should see a doctor for further evaluation of the skin rash or red patches.

Let's continue to see what else we are working with.

14.header: Did it start after a tingling or itchy sensation?

15.header:
Yes?
You may start setting your eyes on shingles.

Symptoms of shingles include rash after:

  • Burning or painful sensation
  • Tingling or itchy sensation

16.header: Are the rash like blisters on red patches of the skin?

17.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • More than likely looking at shingles
  • Treatment has to be started early within 72 hrs of blisters appearing.

Symptoms usually begin with pain along the affected areas on one side of the body, followed in 2 to 3 days by red patches of the skin which quickly develop blisters on them. This is usually diagnostic.

To reduce complications, treatment has to be started early with antiviral and possibly steroids within 24 hours of feeling pain or burning, and preferably before the blisters appear.

If it is more than 72 hours of the blister appearing, then this treatment is unlikely to be effective.

18.header: What about blisters or rash from the spine to the front of the belly?

19.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possibly looking at shingles.

20.header: Are you looking at blisters or rash from spine to the front of the chest?

21.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possibly sign of shingles.

22.header: Is the blisters or rash on one side of the face or forehead?

23.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to reduce severe complications if it is shingles.
  • Blisters or rash on the face requires urgent care. If you suspect anything like that, then you should seek urgent medical attention.

Would you like to see the nearest urgent care facility or Continue?

24.header: Is the blisters or rash on one side of the mouth, eyes or ears?

25.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to reduce severe complications

Would you like to see the nearest urgent care clinic or Continue?

26.header:
Alright
Let's see how else you feel and if this will tell you something.

Or do you think you should seek urgent care from the discussions so far?

30.header: Do you feel weakness on one side of the face in addition to a rash and pain?

31.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible symptom of shingles.
  • There is a possibility of some nerves on your face getting affected.

You should suspect Shingles or at least see a doctor if any of these is applicable to you:

  • One-sided burning, pain, tingling or itching
  • Painful, blistering rash
  • Facial muscle getting weak

Take this seriously especially if you have difficulty moving some of the muscles in the face.

32.header:
What about fever, chills, headaches?

In addition to a painful rash on one side of the body?

33.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possibly looking at shingles.
  • This require urgent care.

34.header: Are you looking at burning, reddish looking marks like someone bit or scratched you?

35.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at shingles rash.

You should suspect shingles or at least see a doctor if any of these is applicable to you:

  • One-sided burning, pain, tingling or itching
  • Painful, blistering rash
  • Facial muscle getting weak
  • Reddish looking bites with burning

36.header: Are you thinking sunburn blisters and you have a headache?

37.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Could be shingles especially if a possible sunburn could be ruled out.

You should suspect shingles or at least see a doctor if any of these is applicable to you:

  • One-sided burning, pain, tingling or itching
  • Painful, blistering rash
  • Facial muscle getting weak
  • Reddish looking bites with burning
  • Thinking sunburn blisters with headache.

38.header: Do you have blisters in the ear and is your hearing getting affected?

39.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Suspecting shingles.

You should suspect shingles or at least see a doctor if any of these is applicable to you:

  • One-sided burning, pain, tingling or itching
  • Painful, blistering rash
  • Facial muscle getting weak
  • Reddish looking bites with burning
  • Thinking sunburn blisters with headache.
  • Blisters in the ear
  • Hearing is getting affected

40.header: Are you losing your sense of vision or taste?

41.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to reduce complications if it is shingles.

You should suspect shingles or at least see a doctor if most of these apply to you:

  • One-sided burning, pain, tingling or itching
  • Painful, blistering rash
  • Facial muscle getting weak
  • Reddish looking bites with burning
  • Thinking sunburn blisters with headache.

42.header: What about general ill-feeling with a painful rash?

43.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • A sign and symptom of shingles.

44.header: Are you over the age of 60 and experiencing a burning rash?

45.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

You should suspect shingles or at least see a doctor if any of these is applicable to you:

  • One-sided burning, pain, tingling or itching
  • Painful, blistering rash
  • Facial muscle getting weak
  • Reddish looking bites with burning
  • Thinking sunburn blisters with headache.
  • Blisters in the ear

  • Over the age of 60

46.header: Do you have abdominal pain in addition to a painful rash?

47.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out shingles.

48.header: What about swollen glands with a painful rash?

49.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out shingles.

50.header:
A,
Those were signs and symptoms of shingles.

If you suspect shingles, see a doctor as soon as possible by going to the nearest urgent care clinic or emergency room. Don't try to ride it out.

Suspect shingles if any of these apply to you:

  • Current going through stress.

  • One-sided burning, pain, tingling or itching.

  • Painful, blistering rash.

  • Facial muscle getting weak.

  • Reddish looking bites with burning.

  • Thinking sunburn blisters and you have a headache.

  • Blisters in the ear.

  • Hearing is getting affected.

  • Losing your sense of vision and/or taste.

  • Over the age of 60

Would you like to see the nearest urgent care facility to you?

Nothing over the counter will take care of this.
